result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.descr: Records of prosec. are converted data. See file.

records.addlTxt: Case called along with 14CF394.  Defendant Christopher J. Williams in court with attorney Greg E. Vollan.  James T. Sempf appeared for the State of Wisconsin.    The Court reviewed CPR and PQWOR and heard plea of No Contest to Poss. of  a Controlled Subst., 2nd or Subseq. Offense.  Ct. found plea was given FKVI, accepted plea, and found Def guilty of the charge. Court found factual basis in the Crim. Compl./Info.  Based upon his plea to Count 1 in 14CF110, Ct. 2 and Case No. 14CF394 are DRI. The Court heard from State and Defense and ordered the matter continued for six months to allow the defendant an opportunity to obtain treatment.  He's to return with proof of his progress with his drug treatment plan.  Bond to continue.
Defendant shall not consume alcohol or other intoxicants.  Defendant must maintain absolute sobriety.

Defendant Christopher J. Williams in custody via video with attorney Greg E. Vollan (will appoint).  James T. Sempf appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant has received copy of Criminal Complaint and advised of rights, charges, penalties and right to Preliminary Hearing. Court finds probable cause. Prelim requested waiving time limits. Prelim 1/22/15 at 8:30am in Br. 3; Court sets bond at $1,000.00 PA BOND with conditions:   Defendant shall not consume alcohol or other intoxicants.  Defendant must maintain absolute sobriety.
